The South African bond market was weaker at midday on Friday as higher US treasury yields continued to exert pressure on local yields. The yield on the benchmark 10-year US treasury weakened 4.32% to 2.1509% from 2.0619% on Thursday. US markets were closed on Friday due to the Veteran s Day holiday. At 11.30am the R186 was bid at 9.130% from 9.000%. The R207 was bid at 8.315% from 8.160%. Momentum SP Reid analysts said US treasury yields broke sharply higher as investors speculated about the potential inflationary effect of a substantial fiscal programme for the US in the years ahead. &#8220;This comes against the backdrop of an increasingly hawkish tone by members of Federal Reserve s federal open market committee &#8221; Momentum said. The market is anticipating a US rate hike in December. The short-term pickup in yields could be partially overdone from a technical perspective arguing for a slight retracement Momentum said. The yield on the benchmark R186 bond crossed the 9% mark for the first time in weeks on Thursday as fears mounted over possible aggressive rate increases in the US under Donald Trump who has indicated he was in favour of fiscal stimulus. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Related Share on Facebook Share Share on Twitter Tweet Share on Google Plus Share